OL,6,FMeanwhile the BBC and the other major
OL,7,Fbroadcasters are not echo chambers `
OL,8,Fthey are the public spaces we all have
OL,9,Fstakes in and where any opinion which
OL,10,Fis respectfully expressed should have a
OL,11,Fplace.
OL,13,FThe row over Gary Lineker's tweet and
OL,14,Fthe BBC's response sits at the centre
OL,15,Fof this.
OL,17,FThere is an alarming tendency in
OL,18,Fcertain quarters to see the world in
OL,19,Fblack and white ` you are either
OL,20,Fcompletely and unquestioningly for
OL,21,Fsomething or against it.
OL,3,CImpartiality and the BBC in the age of
OL,4,Csocial media
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}        G2/10
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,34503
SC,0003
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F345A1679356768
OL,6,FThere is no need to understand where an
OL,7,Fopponent is coming from, far less a
OL,8,Fneed to engage constructively with
OL,9,Ftheir arguments and accept they might
OL,10,Fhave a point. You are either for
OL,11,Fsomething or against it.
OL,13,FIn this toxic environment, demonising
OL,14,Fopponents or saying things online which
OL,15,Fno decent person would say to someone's
OL,16,Fface is considered acceptable.
OL,18,FMark Chapman highlighted the abuse some
OL,19,FBBC Sport colleagues had received over
OL,20,Fthe weekend.
OL,3,CImpartiality and the BBC in the age of
OL,4,Csocial media
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}        G3/10
